on and replication inside host cells, framing their biological impact\",\"explanation\":\"Virus is described as an acellular entity that cannot be clearly classified as living or non-living, containing nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) enclosed in a protein capsid, lacking metabolic organelles, and becoming active only inside host cells where it reproduces by producing many viral particles. This definition frames why viruses are impactful: they depend on host cells for activity and propagation, which links directly to disease and infection contexts in the rest of the community. [Data: Entities (1336)].\\n\\nThe presence of a “virus-infected cell” entity reinforces that viral activity is contextualized in host cells, aligning with the description that viruses become active only inside host cells. [Data: Entities (1345)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Protein capsid is a core structural component anchoring the community’s ‘virus structure’ concept\",\"explanation\":\"The protein capsid is described as the protein coat enclosing viral nucleic acid, and the relationships explicitly state that a virus consists of nucleic acid enclosed by a protein capsid. This makes “protein capsid” the primary structural node connected to the virus definition, emphasizing composition and architecture as a key theme in the community. [Data: Entities (1337, 1336); Relationships (1878)].\\n\\nBy explicitly linking the capsid to viral nucleic acid enclosure, the community underscores a minimal structural model of viruses (genetic material + capsid) without adding other structures or lifecycle steps beyond what is described. [Data: Relationships (1878); Entities (1336, 1337)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Electron microscopy is positioned as the necessary technical capability to observe viruses and infected cells\",\"explanation\":\"The electron microscope is described as a high-resolution tool recommended for viewing small biological structures (including cell organelles) and is stated to be necessary for studying viruse